text:
for over 3 years myself and 6 others were part of an account called _homo_intended_. it was hacked at 9.7k followers, and we lost the entire account, as well as our posts, memories, and all the people who followed and interacted with us. luckily i have this account (previously @that_queer_transboy) that i changed into the new _homo_intended_. for now it will just me me and @queen_kebin running this account, but once we figure out things we may add admins. as hard as it is to lose our beloved safe space, we are back and we are not going to give up. the account was created so we can help others, advocate for our community, and have a safe space to express ourselves. a hacker tried to take that from us, but we are back now and ready to make the account even better than it was before. -dawson

text:
i find it hard to photograph the iridescence of these mugs. i finally was able to capture it (swipe to see) with the new cfl light set up that @daedal_goods uses and was kind enough to share with me! .
.
.
these mugs are #sexualabuseawareness mugs. no one likes to think or discus the issue of sexual abuse but it is unfortunately something that almost every woman i know deals with and a handful of men too. i wanted this line of big ass mugs to be bright and happy, i intentionally let the â€œmine not yoursâ€ crack. the cracks to me represent how sexual abuse can try and destroy you, how it can break you down and leave behind wounds that can heal but will always be there. the bright and beautiful pink and crisp lines represents how woman are incredibly resilient, how no matter what is thrown at us we come together and we conquer the assaults! as a child of sexual abuse, this is a very important project for me. for every â€œmine not yoursâ€ mug that is purchased, a art therapy session will available to someone in need. ğŸ’• #metoo

text:
coined in 2006 by @taranajaneen as the start of efforts to address abuse of black women and girls. 11 years later it became a hashtag as droves of mostly white women began outing mostly white men about historical incidents of sexual harassment and assault. sure, bring awareness by any means necessary, but burke's initiative has been lost in the sea of #womensissues and at most is only implied in discussions about abuse of #womenofcolor . every time we allow ourselves to simply  occupy a room in the #minority and #peopleofcolor house, we realize too late that our room is in the sealed-off basement. black folks we have our own house. let's get it in order. .

text: my grandmother passed away today. she suffered very much for a long time, so while losing her is painful, there is also gratitude for the end of her suffering. this loss brings up more pain from other life events, and itâ€™s a challenge to not turn away but instead lean into the unfolding raw experiences of this life and this death, with gentleness and curiosity. there seems to simultaneously be a lot and nothing at all to say. yesterday a guy in a bar behaved very inappropriately toward me and my friend, and didnâ€™t stop even when clearly told. in the end we got him thrown out from the bar, but he had already stepped over our boundaries several times by then. at the time, i only felt murderous anger, but afterwards i realized how deeply frightening and hurtful it had been to not have my boundaries respected. i donâ€™t know whether it would have mattered to him or not if heâ€™d known that i was about to face a death in my family, but i like to think that when we behave with violence towards others we do so because of our ignorance. we forget that every person we encounter will lose absolutely everything that they love including their self, and when we forget that, itâ€™s easy to end up treating others (and ourselves) without kindness and respect. may this pain serve to help us remember to be honest with ourselves about life and how we treat the people we come across. and may we all act to bring more consciousness, warmth and curiosity into this world to heal the sources of any ignorance and coldness that we find. #metoo #timesup #death #opening #surrenderbeyondwords #radicaldharma #fuckviolence #consent #consentculture #consentlegislationnow #letsgetreal

text:
hypocrisy of current advocacy
#metoo #teenagepregnancy #saynotochildmarriage #educationnotexploitation #endchildlabour 
all eloquent coinages depicting decades struggles of inequality, exploitation and abuse but largely an inadequate, selfish and myopic representation of the urgency required to tackle this menace. however, the greatest obstacle to securing our rights and place in society is us, women and advocates.

proliferation of advocacy organizations
aptly, too many cooks spoil a good pudding. such a significant menace requires, nay, demand an urgent action. however, the purpose of the fight, its necessity and its possibilities has been diverted to one of money making and a matter of status. a situation to prove a humanitarian spirit that is lacking in most. an opportunity to be ceos, executive directors and chairs of foundations by people with little grasp of tools that accords them with leverage to make actual progress and change. can you as supporters of a cause not make the same impact (if not more) by aligning with other organizations with the means, methods and network? 
backbiting & battle for supremacy
the very essence of advocacy has now been diverted to mean â€œthe one with the most fame, awards and moneyâ€. postings are now about those following trends, been the most angry about issues of abuse but then doing a disappearing act when it comes to actually supporting, funding for significant impact and initiating ventures that guarantees change. most unfortunate is the habit of rumor mongering & back biting those considered threats to their own supremacy and recognition.
the questions remain, who made advocacy about benefiting? who made it about popularity or one with most awards? 
lessons
when will women learn that this world was wired for men and padded for men and that level of comfort is promoted by women who harbor and circulate hate and misrepresentation of colleagues? 
when will women consider it their responsibility to instill goodness and gentleman behaviors at an early age onto the character of our boys who become the men who abuse us and our younger counterparts?
when will women consider it their responsibility to instill value and confide

text:
the grand temple of murudeshwara is located on the banks of the arabian sea in north karnataka. 18 storeys high, a beach with clean blue water and a gigantic statue of shiva just adjacent to the ocean makes it one of the most picturesque structures in the country.

i made it a point to visit this temple town during my goa-gokarna trip last month. for those visiting gokarna (esp people who like to click), murudeshwara is just 70-75 kms away and is one of the destinations which is too good miss. - shot on google pixel 3xl #teampixel

text:
#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear itâ€™s a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they donâ€™t own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. â€œthere is no greater threat to women than men? weâ€™re the number one threat!â€ said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking â€œlook at all that she can do for herselfâ€. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult

text: so many great things have happened since the #metoo movement first started a little over a year ago. we wouldnâ€™t be in this moment without the incredibly brave silence breakers- the women and men who spoke out and named an abuser.  i know that iâ€™m in a very fortunate position with my career right now, but thatâ€™s not the case for a lot of people who have been integral in this movement. most have been pushed down in our business (or out altogether), which is sickening since we know that if they had just complied or remained silent, they might be at the top of the town today. they spoke out, and because of the power and support of social media, the people who run this industry have been forced to make changes. their names should be the ones headlining movies. they should be given the opportunities to do award-nominating work. they should be paid top dollar. and anyone in a position to elevate them should do it.

text:
i've been thinking about the process of healing lately. partly, because meghan and i have been going through a process of healing, but also many new and old friends are going through their own journeys.

healing is a process that never ends. the trauma changes us. it redirects us to new places. sometimes our journeys are interrupted by new trauma or by forms of coping that hurt us more. 
almost every week, something challenges meghan and i in a new way. that sets us back. i live with the constant fear that the next something will throw us back into the chaos and hopelessness of a couple years ago. 
far too often in my life, my weakness has allowed fear to shut me down, to let that fear win. fear divides us, it turns some of us into monsters. 
how do we overcome that fear? maybe, not overcome. how do we keep the momentum of healing? 
love. hope. relation. being heard, being seen. some days, our healing is a personal journey. sometimes our trauma demands isolation. but there will always be a time that our hurt needs to be heard, seen, validated, and healed through the ways we relate to others. 
that, to me, is how we need to envision community. trauma may have ended a part of me, but healing has given me a way to see through this, together. 
what does your heart and head need to heal? how do we create a society in which cycles of trauma aren't the norm?
name: Trevor Pruitt-Steele

that, to me, is how we need to envision community. trauma may have ended a part of me, but healing has given me a way to see through this, together. 
what does your heart and head need to heal? how do we create a society in which cycles of trauma are not the norm?

text: #youdoyou. sounds easy, right. guess what, it isn't. people love to throw phrases around that they read on facebook. feel the #meaning behind it? no. i heard this and other phrases before, but i'm just slowly learning to actually feel them. it's a long #journey i'm on, but it's the right one. you'll have #collateraldamage along the way of #selfdiscovery my #therapist told me. my social workers asked me to be cautious of possible bachkash i might receive when i stand my ground. open up to my feelings, voicing my needs. they were right. i knew in the back of my head as well. #selfsacrifice is what i did all my life. living the life for others than myself. besides my parents nobody actually demanded this... well, maybe my #ex. but seriously: fack him. sure, i let that #sexualabuse happen. sure,  i let #mentalabuse happen, but i never asked for it. also i never asked anybody to take advantage of me or my situation. i'm learning that it's ok to be angry. it's ok to admit being a #victim. i am not #desperate anymore. i am not ashamed anymore. yet, strangely i still feel the need to explain myself. still afraid people won't believe me. a lot of people do, but #rape, #sexualabuse is such a sensitive topic many don't understand. are scared of even, because this is something that doesn't happen in their life. they shut it out. for me, it is reality. when the #metoo movement started, i was like yeah. i thought i was alone with that. i am male, how could this happen to me? the truth is, the #abuse starts with a no. if it doesn't end there, it's #abuse. i want and am getting better. holding on...

text: someone recently reached out to me about a bulk order of these pins. she shared her #metoo story with me and it broke my heart. i designed these pins before the 2016 election, before #metoo , in a different headspace in a different world. i was so sad to hear her story but i was elated that she related so much to this pin and that she truly felt empowered. i cannot believe the politics of today but the best we can do is stay woke, vote with your dollar, volunteer, and talk to each other. donating to causes near and dear and buying a stranger a coffee will also probably help the world be a better place â˜•ï¸

 what are your rituals?

a ritual is a ceremony, a practice, an act of worship. but what are we honoring in our rituals? in our daily practices? are we celebrating what serves us, or do we make too much time for thoughts and habits and people that detract from our highest selves?

text:
the next time i hold my pen
i promise,
i won't let my words meet you
the horizon, maybe
not you.
but today i let them loose
turns out,
you're the rulerÂ 
they crave to slave for.Â 
funny how,
my definition of love went from
prince charming with perfect smile
to goofy grin with unkempt stubble;
or maybe i should justÂ 
write my own fairytale,
only that my prince charming has
crooked tooth
and his eyes do not twinkle
'like stars in a midnight sky'
my own fairytale,
only that the princess is not
a damsel in distressÂ 
but a hopeless romanticÂ 
playing around with imperfect words
until they make senseÂ 
my own fairytale,
only that cinderella's shoe
may not always fit
but her words do.Â 
but,Â 
this is the last timeÂ 
i say that,
because,
the next time i hold my pen
i promise,
i won't let my words meet you
the moon, maybe
not you.
or maybe that's what i'll sayÂ 
the next time,
and the nextÂ 
and the nextÂ 
until i'm finallyÂ 
out of love.
.
.
shruti singh.
(@the.pragmatic.idiot)
.
.
.

text:
for those who have asked what i want for the holidays, honestly: 
clemency for cyntoia brown

yes, it is just one case in a larger flawed justice system where there is work to be done, but i believe this case represents a bigger truth of american history.

as this story resurges now and again over the years, many people say, â€œhow can this happen to a child?â€ â€œhow can the system have failed her so terribly?â€ this brings to mind the work â€œcontested relations: slavery, sex, and medicineâ€ where dr. deirdre cooper owens unpacks the cultural and legal ways that, during american slavery and after, there was no such concept as rape or consent for black women or girls (unless they as â€œpropertyâ€ were damaged, which created an economic case for their owners tied to reproduction). black women and girls were seen as sexual and laboring objects, not whole humans deserving of consent, affirmation of emotional trauma, and acknowledgement of abuse â€” let alone justice. these are the very values that were built into our justice system. imagine being a child having nowhere to go for support other than your community rendered powerless. here we are 200 years later with those very values still subversively and clearly present in the court, in medical practice, etc.

there is so much to say about this case, but it is not just cyntoia brown, it is many lesser known stories of women and girls. it is part of the american story.

please contact the office of governor bill haslam (who is reviewing the case) at âœ‰ï¸ 1st floor state capital nashville, tn 37243 or ğŸ“ 615-741-2001 or @governorbillhaslam 
you can also sign the moveon petition

about the case:
cyntoia brown was a 16 year old child being sex trafficked in 2004 when tried as an adult for the murder of a man who paid to rape her. last week, tennessee supreme court ruled that she will serve at least 51 years in prison before being eligible for release. you can watch â€œme facing life: cyntoiaâ€™s storyâ€ for a deeper understanding.

#cyntoiabrown #believewomen #believeblackwomen #metoo #justice #socialjustice #sexworkerrights #protectchildren #healthartactivism #thisisamerica #blm #clemencyforcyntoia

exchange on the experience.

text:
@regran_ed from @elishaattai -  thank you guys for coloring my birthday  positively this morning with such impactful awareness walk #womendecide in partnership with yali lagos team to pass across the message of women's crucial role in electoral decision making.

like i said earlier, african women involvement in politics and leadership will not just benefits women alone, but the continent as a whole.

the enlightened women of africa in partnership with the enlightened men will change and disrupt the system.

thank you once again to my tireless team, awlo members, yali lagos, the distinguished speakers, cadbury nigeria and our media partners!@yaliwestafrica @yalinetworklag @awloint @stbensonimoh @ebakpakpan @nkajimangewe @aitonlineng @ltvsocial @vanguardnews @tribuneonlineng @guardiannigeria - #regrann

text:
my fourth and final person of 2018â€¦ dr. christine blasey ford, the strong and courageous woman who spoke up during the brett kavanaugh confirmation to the us supreme court. she should be the face of the whole #metoo movement.

right from the moment that trump picked kavanaugh to be his new supreme court justice, something didnâ€™t feel right about the guy. his views were a little bit too â€˜conservitiveâ€™ and during the confirmation hearings, he mostly spoke down in a condescending manner to any of the democrat female senators who were interviewing him. but i told myself that the only reason i didnâ€™t like him was because he was trumpâ€™s pick. maybe i should give him a chance?

then came the explosive allegation that he sexually assaulted christine when they were in high school. i still hesitated to pass judgement. both she and kavanaugh were called to testify at a hearing in front of the senateâ€¦ so i watched, and seeing christine up there, in front of the whole world giving her testimony, all i could think was; what a brave and courageous woman. i knew without any doubt that she was 100% telling the truth. she didnâ€™t have to be there, in fact, she wanted to remain anonymous. but there she was, performing her civil duty.
kavanaughâ€™s testimony, by comparison was sloppy and it was scripted. he let emotions like anger and impatience get the better of him, lashing out at some of the senators (a trait that you do not want to see in a sitting supreme court justice), almost like he felt that he was entitled to be a justice. i didnâ€™t believe him for one second! absolute clown.

but in the end, it was all for nought as he still got confirmed. and trump made it a thing to go around after the confirmation and rub it in the faces of the democrats that his guy won. like it was all a game.
christine still gets death threats from ignorant idiotic trump supportersâ€¦ like it was all for nothing. well, i for one will never forget her courageousness or her sense to do what is right.

i wish more people would take a page from the book of dr. christine blasey ford, who in my opinion stuck to her principals and has true strength of character! you go girl! you have earned my reverence too ğŸ‘.

text:
via @cnn - cyntoia brown, who's serving life in prison for killing a man who bought her for sex when she was 16, could still be freed soon.
the tennessee supreme court last week ruled brown would have to serve at least 51 years in prison for the 2004 killing before she's eligible for release.
but amid widespread outrage on social media, gov. bill haslam's office is now reviewing her case. <â€”â€”- proof that we can have a voice and impact. â€”â€”-
what to do now? 
1. go read about the case
2. sign the moveon petition 
3. share your thoughts and links on social media so folks know and can take action 
4. contact gov bill haslamâ€™s office and voice your thoughts 1st floor, state capitol nashville, tn 37243 (615) 741-2001 
5. his instagram @governorbillhaslam (remember, he is considering clemency so letâ€™s honor and encourage that) 
6. watch the video: me facing life: cyntoiaâ€™s story - google it - itâ€™s on @pbs and you can watch it online. â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”

text:
we should be begging,  begging indigenous and first nations peoples to teach us everything they know about living in harmony with #nature 
humans are after all, just another animal on the tree of life. an animal that poisons it's own home. right now, on the ground in the amazon rainforest of ecuador, there's an emergency that will affect every single human being on the planet and not to mention all of sentient life.

with the help of the @pachamamaorg the sÃ¡para have prevented oil extraction in their territory for the past 20 years!! that's a hurculean feat. we owe them a debt of #gratitude. 
unfortunately the government of ecuador recently sold new concessions to the peruvian national oil company, for extraction of oil from their lands. the consequences are potentially fatal for the entire world. they're literally going to destroy the lungs of the earth.

collectively we're going to have to transform the behavior responsible for continuing to drive the destruction of the amazon rainforest. from the sÃ¡para perspective, many of the challenges that humanity is suffering from are due to people not remembering where they come from & being disconnected from the dreams they have each night. meaning our dreams connect us to the collective unconscious, the realm in which we are all one and connected. 
the @pachamamaorg and the sÃ¡para are working to awaken people so that they can see the possibility for and create collective change around the world.  this partnership is critical for both keeping oil development from their lands and for creating a future that works for everybody.

every species is interconnected in the biosphere and the rainforest plays a large part on this planet for keeping the air breathable. when i think of all our good works in the #metoo movement and in #antiracist work, it would all be for naught without a livable planet to share. 
please consider donating either on a regular monthly basis or a one-time donation to the @pachamamaorg  it's urgent. ( you can donate with trust. they manage all contributions to the alliance with the highest level of financial integrity and willl keep you informed about how your resources are used. )

but i cannot.

i cannot forget the way he slept beside me.

this is currently one of the greatest atrocities and oppression taking place in the world today yet still it is one of the most least talked about issues. it's like the world doesn't care. it's possible there are over 2 million #uyghur #muslims who've been sent to these concentration camps which the #chinese government calls education camps. people are tortured and brain washed in these camps and the goal is to remove their cultural and religious identities. the goal is to remove #islam and religion from their hearts.
.
many of the little kids end up being orphaned and sent to government run orphanages and once again they are brainwashed and their cultural and religious identities are completely removed. many of their parents don't make it out alive from the camps due to torture. and those that have come out alive you can hear many of the witness statements of how they were tortured and what really went on in these camps. china sees the #islamic identity of the uyghur muslims as a disease or an illness. it's beyond belief what's happening in east turkestan to our uyghur #muslim brothers and sisters.
.
people can be arrested for the smallest of reasons and everything is under full surveillance. they have facial recognition cameras in the streets and have deployed so many security officers and high tech technology to keep full control or east turkestan. in their own promotional video for the 're-education camps' they had 5 high tech cameras in a single classroom. idk about you but i've never been to school or college and had 5 cameras in my class tracking my every move and every step. people's phones are taken and checked out for any suspicious religious content. there are even occasions where uyghur muslim girls have been forced to marry chinese men. i know this probably happens more often but it has been recorded on a few occasions and they even have a government strategy promoting this inter-marriage between uyghur and han chinese men. there's so much more going on and even stuff that we don't know that it's hard to say. keep them in your prayers .

text:
my periods are like a beautiful song on loop.
beautiful songs are usually painful,
but they make you feel secure, they make you feel tranquil.
their sole actuality makes you feel serene.
just the fact that my periods are alive provides me safety, it gives me the sense of pride.
it flows in a rhythm making me pure,
the only barren space which is filled with respect.
the battery dies and the song pauses,
but i keep humming it in my mind, to cherish it till the time i hear the music again, till the time i perfectly learn to hit the high notes.
.
.

.

text:
this is the witness statement by a uyghur #muslim sister on the torture and abuse she went through inside china's concentration camps. in her full story she talks about how she was arrested multiple times and spent 10 months inside the camps. her kids were taken away from her and once she was released she found out one of her children had died and she was reunited with the other 2. she talks about how she was stripped naked and put in some computerised machine after which then she was dressed in uniform like that of prisoners. she was one one occasion interrogated for 4 days and night and though that she had seizures and loss on consciousness.  they were forced to memorize and recite songs every morning praising #china and it's leader. they were forced to take certain pills and drink some typa liquid which led to loss of menstruation, bleeding, and even death for sone. in her cell there were about 60 people. when they had to sleep 15 people would stand up and the rest would sleep sideways and they would rotate every few hours. and her torture in the tiger chair is mentioned in the above video. she witnessed 9 deaths in her cell in 3 months.
.
in 2018, in the 21st century this is still happening and the world is silent. forget putting a stop to it, no one is even really investigating these crimes. and the few reporters that do go to the province are stopped from recording the camps by chinese police. what do they have to hide if it's just "education camps"?
.
also one thing i don't like is people shouting 'fake news' like #trump to anything that they dont know about. the united nations have spoken about this, china has spoken about the existence of these camps, you have hundreds maybe thousands of people who've given witness statements regarding themselves or their family members who are in these camps, you have #uyghur #muslims who speak about living conditions inside the province. and you tell me every single one of them is lying? stop with the ignorance and go do your research and get some knowledge. share and let the world know what is happening. #islam #quran 
_________________________________

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
menjelang awal tahun 2019 saat sebuah perhelatan perfilman besar bernama academy awards akan diadakan, steve mcqueen kembali menunjukkan keistimewaannya sebagai sutradara dengan "craft" yang luar biasa lewat #widows. berkisah tentang tiga orang janda yang harus melakukan perampokan akibat ditinggal mati suami-suami mereka dengan hutang yang luar biasa besarnya, steve mcqueen mengambil pendekatan kombinasi drama politik dengan heist-thriller untuk menunjukkan kekuatan para wanita independen yang sudah jengah dengan ketidakadilan yang mereka dapatkan dari tokoh-tokoh pria brengsek di sekitar mereka. hasilnya? bombastis, dramatis, menegangkan, dan padat akan pesan.

widows memberikan salah satu penampilan ensemble cast terbaik di tahun ini lewat performa viola davis, michelle rodriguez, dan elizabeth debicki. mereka mempunyai dinamika yang unik. masing-masing berbeda ras, latar belakang, dan tabiat, namun dipersatukan oleh keadaan. mcqueen sabar dan telaten memanfaatkan pengembangan sub-plot di film ini untuk menaikkan intensitas ketegangan sekaligus eksposisi "what's at stake here." gillian flynn yang ikut bekerjasama dalam menulis dan merancang cerita serta penuturannya turut memberikan sentuhan khasnya berupa "plot twist" yang tidak hanya gelap, namun relevan dalam melawan narasi "not all men" yang semakin menjadi-jadi di tengah kampanye #metoo ini. sebagai seorang aktor, daniel kaluuya memberikan salah satu akting terbaiknya lewat karakter jatemme, seorang hitman bengis yang selalu mencoba untuk "bersenang-senang" dalam menyelesaikan tugasnya. namun sebagai sebuah karakter, relevansi keberadaan jatemme begitu lemah, seakan-akan ditulis hanya untuk menominasikan daniel kaluuya di ajang best supporting actor di academy awards tahun depan.

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason

and

fight on your knees.
praise him before the breakthrough.

and trust all of this will be used for your good, as you continually surrender the circumstances over to him.

text: wanna know what floats my boat? mentoring creative talent. our sponsorship of fashion week san diego provides the ultimate venue to do just that with the opening night, the art and beauty behind fashion. this year our stylists teamed up with a designer and makeup artist to create a complete look inspired by paintings supplied by the art renewal center and artists from around the world. the event was hosted here in encinitas at the lux art institute. here my stylists roberta, katrina and ashley created a textured and braided style for janne robinson's painting titled "me too". the style speaks to contrived constructs of feminine beauty, with details that, though noticeable, still fit within for an image of unoffended and graceful fluidity. photo by @656photography

text:
â—ï¸â—ï¸â—ï¸â—ï¸read before you watchâ—ï¸â—ï¸â—ï¸â—ï¸â—ï¸â—ï¸ -
-
-

this one was mainly inspired by the #metoo movement. and the call-out of men and women across the world, victims of sexual harassment.

here is an overview of the creative process behind it:

the main piece takes the shape of a pyramid of perverts, forming an allegorical hierarchy of persecution. 
from the petty fondlers and harassers, at the bottom. to the devious and manipulative big shots, at the top. 
some trying to accaparate the woman for themselves. some united together, in a sinister effort to humiliate her. 
all in a flurry of overwhelmingly libidinous power, towards what they obviously consider a mere sexual object.

regarding the circle of characters surrounding it. it is both a metaphorical representation of us as a society, and a recursion, of an hypothetical audience, attending the installation, from their own point of view. 
all of them trying to turn a blind eye on the direct issue, or rather threat, that they are experiencing.
in a vain attempt to coward away from the scene, they only find themselves hopeless, in front of a mirror.
constrained to watch the tragedy, but also contemplate their own reflection.

as a final word. i would like to clarify, that this is an issue i have only been exterior of. 
this is not me, speaking in the name of oppressed women. but rather my own harsh perspective as a man. based on observation towards beings of my own gender.
#videoedits #metoo #metoomovement #edits #edits #animation

text:
december 13 maybe just a normal day like other days. it is the 81 years anniversary of the nanjing massacre, or rape of nanjing. it was an episode of mass murder and rape committed by japanese troops against the residents of nan jing, then the capital of china, during the second sino-japanese war. 
i read a story of a comfort woman-tatoo and i will never forget it. the true story is disturbingğŸ’”it reveals some truths about what happened in the past and how it continued to impact the person for the rest of their lives. there are many chinese and korean women are forced to be â€œcomfort womenâ€ during that time. this made me sad, angry and powerless. 
according to china comfort women issue research center, only 6 comfort women had survived in china by 2018. when the number becomes 0, will this part of history also be forgotten? it took many years for people to admit this massacre really happened.this has always caused tension between china and japan. 
those events are on my textbooks and i learn about them from my history class. we have ceremonies to remember those who lost their lives during a time without humanity. the past make who we are now, a countryâ€™s past is part of its stories today. 
it is hard to talk about history and politics especially if you are not the person who are impacted directly, who cares what happened so many years ago? 
however, if we donâ€™t care, we donâ€™t admit the mistakes that have been made by our ancestors, the history will repeat itself again. 
here are some facts:

the massacre occurred over a period of six weeks starting on december 13, 1937.

since most japanese military records on the killings were kept secret or destroyed shortly after the surrender of japan in 1945, historians have been unable to accurately estimate the death toll of the massacre. china's official estimate is more than 300,000 dead.

for full story about the comfort woman, click this link:
http://foxtalk.tistory.com/m/98

text:
"respect yourself by respecting others." -miya yamanouchi ,Â embrace your sexual self: a practical guide for women (2015)

i have a topic i would like to share, and it is something i feel strongly about.
did you know 77% of woman exp verbal sexual harassment at some point in their life, in men its 34%, and even then some more in both probably.
(i am not setting aside physical assault either those statistics are just as validated im just isolating this issue specifically.)
i myself come from a long history of sexual abuse growing up, and one sexually violent relationship. 
did you know to that people often don't see the signs weither its socially or even in the workplace to???
i mean how can you prepare yourself to exp being the victim or seeing it happen anyways? even with training, being taught growing up etc.
the best thing you can do is if you see someone is confused/uncomfortable, or asking for it to stop is to step in and help...even if you are uncomfortable.
some people even take it as, "they were just joking." and thats even more sad.
i had the lovely exp with this this past week, even though my man stuck up for me twice, i ended up having to put my foot down in the end (and behave in a way i normally don't act to get my point acrossed that i will be respected, and it is disgusting.)
and of course said person retaliated...which is very common to btw.
the situation has been taken care of! minus some panic attacks later i am ok, but still abit on edge. even though i have moved on from parts of my pasts they still have nasty side effects every blue moon...and it sucks but you can't control other peoples nastieness, but how you react and take action is what is important!
don't keep quiet about unwanted sexual remarks, or assault. its not fricken cool, and i am glad i have strong bones to not tolerate being pushed around like bait.
this is a call for all woman to be strong and feirce. your a rose garden with thorns, not dirt under someones fingernails.
#metoo #notcool #dontkeepquiet #sexualharassmentawareness  #speakout #helpeachother #bestrong #bebrave #becourageous #empowerwoman #tourvoicematters

as you prepare to leave your abuser, make sure you know where your money is.
when you begin planning to leave your abusive partner, money will likely be a major concern. your partner might be financially abusing you by controlling the household finances, not allowing you to work, or forcing you to work and taking your money, or using your credit.
it might seem daunting, but there are ways you can keep your assets safe and accessible in the future. everything from bank accounts, retirement funds, insurance and investments to your credit cards, property, and vehicles should be considered, if there is time, before you make the final move to separate. suffice it to say, the step should only be taken if itâ€™s safe to do so, thatâ€™s is, if you can do them without raising the suspicion of your abuser or putting yourself in added danger. â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€” #lifestyle #family #loveshouldnthurt #december #enddv #byui #dvfacts #dancing #entrepreneur #fall #design #wellness #marketing #friends #idaho #timesup #metoo #idaho #health #breakthesilence #idaho #graphicdesign #healthy #winter

that last summer. that summer where the sun bled out from the sky and much like a prism, spilled it's colourful contents over every atom in existence. 
on to every leaf, on all the trees, the world over.
but not on me.
that summer i didn't go crazy but i wore it very, very, very close. - ns

text:
why i wrote angels in the or:  what dying taught me about healing, survival and transformation: part ii (available in may 2019)

i wrote this book for so many darn reasons.  1) yes, near-death experiences should be a deeper part of the cultural consciousness. we need a variety of speakers talking about afterlife experiences. those of us without a fear of death can bring much comfort to people. 2) spiritual phenomenon such as angel guidance and mediumship can be a greater part or our cultural conversations. the other side offers us all great healing directly.  3) i also wrote this book because i was a young woman who experienced sexual assault in a foreign country. those of us who have survived sexual trauma and worked deeply on healing trauma can push national and global conversations about this subject to help enact real changes in how women are treated in court systems around the globe.  it isnâ€™t â€œfocusing on the negativeâ€ when you are actively working to make this world a safer place for others. 4) i wrote this book because teaching was my mission from god. good teachers need more recognition for all the work they do to help others.  5) i wrote this book because i hate the adage, â€œthose who canâ€™t do, teach.â€ ohâ€¦...whatever.  i have over twenty-five years in education, and i am so excited about my publisher and book cover. i used george orwell, frank mccourt, and steven king as inspiration.  they all taught school for many years, but they also proved that they could both teach and do!  i beat the odds to inspire my students to keep beating odds. 6) i wrote this book because i had the support of god, my ancestors (especially my dad and grandfather) and so many amazing spiritual supporters along the way. louise hay, david foster wallace, and robin williams showed up in spirit to encourage me at different times. this journey has been magical ğŸ’« every journey is!!
.

do you see yourself as amazing and strong?

personally i'm one of the strongest people i know. i dont intend to toot my own horn, but i've been to hell and back more than once. and i've made the choice to get back up, after many falls. most of the time this has been painfully hard.

i choose to celebrate my victories whether big or small. to focus on my positives rather than feed the negatives.

are you your own hero? do you realize how far you have come?

text:
if there is anything iâ€™ve learned in this season, it is that being a truth-teller is not being divisive.

speaking the truth is only destruction to those that are content right where theyâ€™re at. truth is freedom. bringing light to a situation is not gossip. it is unifying. well, it should be.

there are more people that want to shut you up than listen to you. thatâ€™s real. contentment in wondering, assuming and gossip rather than listening and seeking to understand is a way of life for many.

speak. the. truth.

iâ€™m praying for a generation to say, â€œyou know what?...thatâ€™s not right. we swept that under the rug, and it was wrong. letâ€™s listen, love, and change.â€ my truth and what i canâ€™t get off my mind right now is iâ€™ve experienced and seen ladies that love jesus, have leadership skills, are talented and experienced yet still are overlooked by the â€œchurchâ€ for employment....using one verse to justify.

itâ€™s me. itâ€™s a friend. itâ€™s a mentor. itâ€™s a instafriend. itâ€™s every woman in the south iâ€™ve encountered trying to make a living in the house of worship.
iâ€™ve had enough.

jesus lifted the heads of women and poured his spirit out on men and women. my â€œroleâ€ in that is to walk in that. tradition can go move on....let the truth walk in.

i could tell you story after story of my own and others that are told that they will be paid less and receive less respect because of their gender...within the working context of the church.

my father sees this...and he tells me â€œgo get it. i made you to declare my truthâ€. my father in heaven and my father on earth never held me back, and i will never hold my future daughter back.if she has fire in her bones, how dare i hold her back.

iâ€™ll tell her...â€speak the truth even if your voice shakes.â€ iâ€™m rooting for you, women. iâ€™m rooting for the men that want to team up and not push down. bless those men, theyâ€™re not scared.

my voice is shaking, but iâ€™ll keep talking if you need to.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company â€œweaponisedâ€ the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how usersâ€™ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms â€“ facebook, in particular â€“ were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaignâ€™s lesser reported â€œweapons of mass destructionâ€. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someoneâ€™s personality. a userâ€™s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call â€œpopulist political signallingâ€. cambridge analytica, which wasÂ shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

this is for every man, woman and child who has a phone or computer. contact tennessee gov bill haslam to grant cyntoia brown clemency. ph: 615-741-2001 email: bill.haslam@tn.gov â€¢

sheâ€™s not the only one who needs our help but sheâ€™s the one we can help right now. you are one person. an individual. we are a population. a movement. our singular actions are impactful as we realize the bigger picture. please make your voice heard and fight for this child who has more than earned the right for freedom. â€¢ ***warning: this may be triggering***
iâ€™ve stayed silent for years. even through the #metoo movement. the stories of pain and triumph were covering the news and i was frozen. stuck in fear and shame for not speaking up. for not calling out the man who hurt me â€œsoon enoughâ€. for not immediately going to the hospital to have a rape kit done but instead showering and trying to scrub off the last 24 hrs of hellish memories, my shame, my own skin. trying to erase the trauma, fully knowing that i was washing away any evidence that could help my case should i take him to court. i spent the next year debating the length of my life. the day i chose survival, i chose just that; to survive. i never realized there was more until recently. thriving is what we can do. thatâ€™s our choice in life. we can allow ourselves to have passions and joy and to live above fear and shame and pride because weâ€™re the only ones who can suppress our inner-selves. â€¢

survival is what cyntoia fought for and won. the freedom to choose how she lives her life is what you can fight for. â€¢

here is my request: please donâ€™t like this post or comment. instead, spend the 1-2 minutes you would take on a comment or take a fraction of the next 30 minutes youâ€™d probably spend scrolling through this app and type an email to bill haslam. do it for cyntoia. she needs your thoughts and actions most right now.

text: we got our #metoo poster up that was created during our women's forum!! it's on the ceiling in front of the bar, so if you'd like to add to it, write (or print out) your story on some paper and ask the bartender for some tape so you can add it!! we hope seeing this helps some find their voice and the courage to use it and helps others to truly listen and think twice before acting. we are a #safezone in so many different ways, but specifically to this point, we will not allow people to come in and prey on others having a good time! if you ever need help or are being made to feel uncomfortable or unsafe, alert one of our staff so we can intervene!! #7sbgsafezone #7sbg #whyididnttell #ibelieveher #7sbgcrew

text:
morgan spurlock settles suit over unproduced tnt docuseries, will pay turner nets $1.18m
##metoo #breaking news #legal #morgan spurlock #tnt #turner entertainment networks #warrior poets #who rules the world
oscar- and emmy-nominated documentarian morgan spurlock has agreed to pay more than $1.17 million to turner entertainment networks to settle a lawsuit over a female-focused docuseries he ended up not making. the project was shelved after he posted a confessional essay as the #metoo movement was gaining strength. the settlement (read it here) ends turnerâ€™s lawsuit over the planned tnt docuseries who rules the world, whose logline says was to be aboutÂ the most divisive and complicated issues facing women today, from the policing of their bodies and judgments of their family planning choices to the micro-aggressions they face in the media, the workplace and everyday life. shutterstock production on the projectÂ was suspended a year ago after its producers severed ties with spurlock. that move came days after the super size me filmmaker posted a lengthy manifesto in which he admitted to beingÂ â€œpart of the problemâ€ as sexual harassment allegations were exploding all over hollywood. in his postÂ spurlock gave his thoughts on sexual harassment and how heroes had fallen for their indiscretions, asking, â€œwhen will they come for me?â€ fallout was swift and merciless as youtube pulled out of funding spurlockâ€™s super size me 2 and sundance dropped the docu sequel from its 2018 lineup. showtime then dropped his park city-bound docuseries the trade,Â which focused on the opioid crisis.Â spurlock that week also stepped down from his production company warrior poets, which also was defendant in theÂ lawsuit turner filedÂ in late march, when the project still was in its early stages.

text:
#otd in 1918 women voted for the first time in a uk general election.

but things were far from being equal: they had to have some wealth and to be over 30 years old to qualify.
there were fears they would out-vote men due to the deaths of wwi which had finished only a month before.

ten years later, in 1928, women were finally given the right to vote on equal terms with men by the equal franchise act.

visit the @museumoflondon to learn more about the suffragettes and their invaluable fight for women's rights.

pictured, a statue of emmeline pankhurst outside the houses of parliament and 
the museum's collab with @tattydevine

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

text:
â€˜pyjamas are forgivingâ€™ by @twinklerkhanna. published by @juggernaut.in (2018).
â€¢
if i hadnâ€™t read a review of this book in @elleindia i would have judged it by its cover & never picked it up in @bahrisons_booksellers. despite thinking it might be a frothy jilly cooper-esque novel set in a south indian wellness resort (new genre alert?) i was pleasantly surprised & genuinely loved this book & was very sad to finish it. the story centres around anshu, a divorcee in her mid-forties returning for her biannual cleanse at shanthamaaya sthalam wellness retreat. however this year her stay is disturbed by the unexpected arrival of her ex-husband & his new (much younger) wife. this could have been just a good account of the difficulties of a failed relationship & the allure & nostalgia of the past, but the novel slowly unravelled to become so much more than that. khannaâ€™s skill is to weave issues in the forefront of contemporary indian social life (homosexuality, islamophobia, gender-based violence & the #metoo movement) into a gentle novel set in the supposedly safe boundaries of a retreat in green, lush & rainy kerala.
â€¢
will appeal to those who have spent extended time at indian wellness retreats (wearing white pyjamas all day long) ğŸ™ğŸ¼

i donâ€™t know how to start this essay. i cried out all my words yesterday, but i they are replenishing now. i wrung out my pain and now they are black icicles dripping from my extremities. 
so, i will start with the fundamentals. a man raped me. this is not a new phenomenon in the world and it is not a new phenomenon in my life. a decade ago, in high school, i had a boyfriend who would viciously torture and rape me. i have to turn my soul to stone to write those words. he fit the textbook definition of a narcissistic manipulator. he became a marine. he has a child now. heâ€™s getting his mba now. iâ€™m still afraid of him now. i never reported him because he made my life hell. i thought he would kill me and my family. he was capable of it. perhaps the biggest miracle of my life is when he broke up with me inexplicably on easter sunday. i want to frame it as some sort of symbolic resurrection, but i just canâ€™t.  maybe this is a narrow view of resurrection, or the tendency of the white evangelical christian church to cast resurrection as all clouds and glory, not the nitty gritty of scars and healing.

anyway. 
i carried those scars for a decade, though they mostly faded. in august, they ripped open and multiplied. another man raped and stalked me. i met him at a mutual friendâ€™s party in the winter, but we didnâ€™t talk at all past that night until we matched on tinder in the summer. he raped me in my home, in my bed. he remains convinced he did no wrong. i remain shattered. i reported the rape, beginning the arduous, still ongoing investigation and legal process. it is a secondary hell. 
i am on the verge of dropping out of school. i started taking medication for my severe depression, ptsd, and suicidality. most days i can barely eat or leave my house, let alone research complex scientific concepts.
just as i didnâ€™t know how to start this essay, i donâ€™t know how to end it. -anonymous
